feature.name: appClientSupport-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables the Liberty server to process client modules and support remote client containers.

feature.name: appSecurity-1.0
feature.description: This feature is superseded by appSecurity-2.0. Support for securing the server runtime environment and applications. This feature enables servlet-3.0 and web application security, support for LDAP and basic user registries, and SSL. To support secure EJB applications, you must add the ejbLite-3.1 feature. When you add this feature to your server, you need to configure a user registry, such as the basic user registry or the LDAP user registry.

feature.name: appSecurity-2.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for securing the server runtime environment and applications; it includes a basic user registry. This feature supersedes appSecurity-1.0 and does not include servlet-3.0 or support for the LDAP user registry. To secure web applications, add the servlet-3.0 feature. To secure EJB applications, add the ejbLite-3.1 feature. To use LDAP, add the ldapRegistry-3.0 feature. When you add the appSecurity-2.0 feature to your server, you need to configure a user registry, such as the basic user registry or the LDAP user registry.

feature.name: appSecurity-3.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for securing the server runtime environment and applications using Security-1.0 as defined in JSR-375.

feature.name: appSecurityClient-1.0
feature.description: Support for securing the client container runtime environment and applications. This feature enables application security, CSIv2 and SSL on the client.

feature.name: audit-1.0
feature.description: The Audit feature is used to report and track auditable events to ensure the integrity of your system.

feature.name: batch-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for the Java Batch 1.0 API specified by JSR-352.

feature.name: batchManagement-1.0
feature.description: This feature provides managed batch support for the Java batch container. This includes the Batch REST management interface, job logging support, and a command line utility for external scheduler integration.

feature.name: beanValidation-1.1
feature.description: The Bean Validation 1.1 specification provides an annotation based model for validating JavaBeans. It can be used to assert and maintain the integrity of data as it travels through an application. This feature is built on top of Apache BVal.

feature.name: beanValidation-2.0
feature.description: The Bean Validation 2.0 specification provides an annotation based model for validating JavaBeans. It can be used to assert and maintain the integrity of data as it travels through an application. This feature is built on top of the Hibernate Validator Engine.

feature.name: bells-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables the configuration of Basic Extensions using Liberty Libraries (BELL).

feature.name: cdi-1.2
feature.description: The Contexts and Dependency Injection specification makes it easier to integrate Java EE components of different types. It provides a common mechanism to inject component such as EJBs or Managed Beans into other components such as JSPs or other EJBs.

feature.name: cdi-2.0
feature.description: The Contexts and Dependency Injection 2.0 specification makes it easier to integrate Java EE components of different types. It provides a common mechanism to inject component such as EJBs or Managed Beans into other components such as JSPs or other EJBs.

feature.name: cloudant-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables connections to Cloudant by providing a connector instance configured in the server configuration, which can be injected or accessed through JNDI. Applications use the Cloudant client library to utilize the connector instance.

feature.name: concurrent-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables the creation of managed executors that allow applications to submit tasks to run concurrently, with thread context that is managed by the application server.It also enables the creation of managed thread factories to create threads that run with the threadcontext of the component that looks up the managed thread factory.

feature.name: constrainedDelegation-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for Kerberos constrained delegation for SPNEGO.

feature.name: couchdb-1.0
feature.description: This feature has been stabilized. The strategic alternative to this feature is the cloudant-1.0 feature. This feature enables connections to CouchDB by providing a connector instance configured in the server configuration, which can be injected or accessed through JNDI. Applications use the ektorp client library to utilize the connector instance to work with CouchDB.

feature.name: distributedMap-1.0
feature.displayName: Distributed Map interface for Dynamic Caching 1.0
feature.description: This feature provides a local cache service which can be accessed through the DistributedMap API. A default cache is bound in JNDI at "services/cache/distributedmap". Caches can be distributed through addition of a network cache provider such as WebSphere eXtreme Scale.

feature.name: ejb-3.2
feature.description: This feature enables support for Enterprise JavaBeans written to the EJB 3.2 specification.

feature.name: ejbHome-3.2
feature.description: This feature enables the use of home interfaces in Enterprise JavaBeans.

feature.name: ejbLite-3.2
feature.description: This feature enables support for Enterprise JavaBeans written to the EJB Lite subset of the EJB 3.2 specification.

feature.name: ejbPersistentTimer-3.2
feature.description: This feature enables the use of persistent timers in Enterprise JavaBeans.

feature.name: ejbRemote-3.2
feature.description: This feature enables the use of remote interfaces in Enterprise JavaBeans.

feature.name: el-3.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for the Expression Language (EL) 3.0.

feature.name: eventLogging-1.0
feature.description: Logs a record of events, such as JDBC requests and servlet requests, and their durations.

feature.name: federatedRegistry-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for federation of multiple user registries.

feature.name: j2eeManagement-1.1
feature.description: This feature allows applications to utilize the interfaces defined in the JSR77 specification.

feature.name: jacc-1.5
feature.description: This feature enables support for Java Authorization Contract for Containers (JACC) version 1.5 In order to add the jacc-1.5 feature to your server, you need to add the third party JACC provider which is not a part of the WebSphere Application Server Liberty profile.

feature.name: jakartaee-8.0
feature.description: This feature combines the Liberty features that support the Jakarta EE 8.0 Platform.

feature.name: jaspic-1.1
feature.description: This feature enables support for securing the server runtime environment and applications using Java Authentication SPI for Containers (JASPIC) providers as defined in JSR-196

feature.name: javaMail-1.5
feature.description: This feature allows applications to utilize the JavaMail 1.5 API.

feature.name: javaMail-1.6
feature.description: This feature allows applications to utilize the JavaMail 1.6 API.

feature.name: javaee-7.0
feature.description: This feature combines the Liberty features that support the Java EE 7.0 Full Platform.

feature.name: javaee-8.0
feature.description: This feature combines the Liberty features that support the Java EE 8.0 Full Platform.

feature.name: javaeeClient-7.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for Java EE 7 Application Client.

feature.name: javaeeClient-8.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for Java EE 8 Application Client.

feature.name: jaxb-2.2
feature.description: This feature enables support for the Java Architecture for XML Binding 2.2 specification, which provides easy mapping of Java classes to XML documents.

feature.name: jaxrs-2.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for Java API for RESTful Web Services. JAX-RS annotations can be used to define web service clients and endpoints that comply with the REST architectural style. Endpoints are accessed through a common interface that is based on the HTTP standard methods.

feature.name: jaxrs-2.1
feature.description: This feature enables support for Java API for RESTful Web Services v2.1. JAX-RS annotations can be used to define web service clients and endpoints that comply with the REST architectural style. Endpoints are accessed through a common interface that is based on the HTTP standard methods.

feature.name: jaxrsClient-2.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for Java Client API for JAX-RS 2.0.

feature.name: jaxrsClient-2.1
feature.description: This feature enables support for Java Client API for JAX-RS 2.1.

feature.name: jaxws-2.2
feature.description: This feature enables support for Java API for XML-Based Web Services 2.2. JAX-WS web services and clients communicate using XML. Annotations can be used to simplify the development of JAX-WS clients and endpoints.

feature.name: jca-1.7
feature.description: This feature enables the configuration of resource adapters to access Enterprise Information Systems (EIS) from applications. The configuration of a resource adapter also includes the configuration of connection factories, administered objects and activation specifications. Any resource adapter that complies with the JCA 1.7 specification or lower can be used. High performance connection pooling is also provided.

feature.name: jcaInboundSecurity-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables security inflow for resource adapters.

feature.name: jdbc-4.0
feature.description: This feature enables the configuration of DataSources to access Databases from applications. Any database that complies with the JDBC 4.0 specification can be used; customized configuration of many specific providers is included. High performance connection pooling is also provided.

feature.name: jdbc-4.1
feature.description: This feature enables the configuration of DataSources to access Databases from applications. Any JDBC driver that complies with the JDBC 4.1, 4.0, 3.0, or 2.x specification can be used; customized configuration of many specific providers is included. High performance connection pooling is also provided.

feature.name: jdbc-4.2
feature.description: This feature enables the configuration of DataSources to access Databases from applications. Any JDBC driver that complies with the JDBC 4.2, 4.1, 4.0, 3.0, or 2.x specification can be used; customized configuration of many specific providers is included. High performance connection pooling is also provided.

feature.name: jdbc-4.3
feature.description: This feature enables the configuration of DataSources to access Databases from applications. Any JDBC driver that complies with the JDBC 4.3, 4.2, 4.1, 4.0, 3.0, or 2.x specification can be used; customized configuration of many specific providers is included. High performance connection pooling is also provided.

feature.name: jms-2.0
feature.description: This feature enables the configuration of resource adapters to access messaging systems using the Java Message Service API. This also includes the configuration JMS connection factories, queues, topics and activation specifications. Any JMS resource adapter that complies with the JCA 1.7 specification can be used.

feature.name: jmsMdb-3.2
feature.description: This feature is superseded by mdb-3.2. Both features provide identical function; only the feature names are different. mdb-3.2 is the preferred feature name.

feature.name: jndi-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables the use of Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) to access server configured resources such as DataSources or JMS Connection Factories. It also allows access to Java primitives configured in the server as a jndiEntry.

feature.name: jpa-2.1
feature.description: This feature enables support for applications that use application-managed and container-managed JPA. This feature includes Java Persistence API 2.1 specification interfaces and container-managed JPA integration. EclipseLink is also included as the default JPA provider implementation.

feature.name: jpa-2.2
feature.description: This feature enables support for applications that use application-managed and container-managed JPA. This feature includes Java Persistence API 2.2 specification interfaces and container-managed JPA integration. EclipseLink is also included as the default JPA provider implementation.

feature.name: jpaContainer-2.1
feature.description: This feature enables support for applications that use application-managed and container-managed JPA. This feature only includes Java Persistence API 2.1 specification interfaces and container-managed JPA integration. This feature does not include a JPA provider implementation.

feature.name: jpaContainer-2.2
feature.description: This feature enables support for applications that use application-managed and container-managed JPA. This feature only includes Java Persistence API 2.2 specification interfaces and container-managed JPA integration. This feature does not include a JPA provider implementation.

feature.name: jsf-2.2
feature.description: This feature enables support for web applications that use the Java Server Faces (JSF) 2.2 framework. This framework simplifies the construction of user interfaces.

feature.name: jsf-2.3
feature.description: This feature enables support for web applications that use the Java Server Faces (JSF) 2.3 framework. This framework simplifies the construction of user interfaces.

feature.name: jsfContainer-2.2
feature.description: This feature enables CDI integrations for web applications that use the Java Server Faces (JSF) 2.2 framework. This feature only includes container integration code for JSF, and does not include any JSF interfaces or implementation. To use this feature, JSF interfaces and implementation must be packaged within web applications that use JSF.

feature.name: jsfContainer-2.3
feature.description: This feature enables CDI integrations for web applications that use the Java Server Faces (JSF) 2.3 framework. This feature only includes container integration code for JSF, and does not include any JSF interfaces or implementation. To use this feature, JSF interfaces and implementation must be packaged within web applications that use JSF.

feature.name: json-1.0
feature.description: This feature provides access to the JavaScript Object Notation (JSON4J) library. The JSON4J library provides a simple Java model for constructing and manipulating data to be rendered as JSON data.

feature.name: jsonb-1.0
feature.description: The Java API for JSON Binding (JSON-B) feature provides a standard for converting between Java objects and JavaScript Object Notation (JSON).

feature.name: jsonbContainer-1.0
feature.displayName: JavaScript Object Notation Binding 1.0 via Bells
feature.description: The Java API for JSON Binding (JSON-B) feature provides a standard for converting between Java objects and JavaScript Object Notation (JSON). The default JSON-B provider is configured via a <bell> which points at a library containing the JSON-B provider JAR file(s).

feature.name: jsonp-1.0
feature.description: The Java API for JSON Processing (JSON-P) feature provides a standardized method for constructing and manipulating data to be rendered in JavaScript Object Notation (JSON).

feature.name: jsonp-1.1
feature.description: The Java API for JSON Processing (JSON-P) feature provides a standardized method for constructing and manipulating data to be rendered in JavaScript Object Notation (JSON).

feature.name: jsonpContainer-1.1
feature.displayName: JavaScript Object Notation Processing 1.1 via Bells
feature.description: The Java API for JSON Processing (JSON-P) feature provides a standardized method for constructing and manipulating data to be rendered in JavaScript Object Notation (JSON). When this feature is enabled, there is no built-in JSON-P provider. Instead, configure a JSON-P provider via a <bell> which points at a library containing the JSON-P provider JAR file(s).

feature.name: jsp-2.2
feature.description: This feature enables support for Java Server Pages (JSPs) that are written to the JSP 2.2 specification. This framework simplifies the construction of user interfaces.

feature.name: jsp-2.3
feature.description: This feature enables support for Java Server Pages (JSPs) that are written to the JSP 2.3 specification. This framework simplifies the construction of user interfaces. Enabling this feature also enables the Expression Language (EL) version 3.0 feature.

feature.name: jwt-1.0
feature.description: This feature allows runtime to create JWT tokens.

feature.name: jwtSso-1.0
feature.description: This feature allows the runtime to produce and consume MP-JWT cookies for authentication.

feature.name: ldapRegistry-3.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for using an LDAP server as a user registry. Any server that supports LDAP Version 3.0 may be used. Multiple LDAP registries can be configured, and then federated to achieve a single logical registry view.

feature.name: localConnector-1.0
feature.description: This feature allows the use of a local JMX connector that is built into the JVM to access JMX resources in the server. The JMX connector can only be used on the same host machine by a client that has the same user ID and the same JDK as the server process. It enables local access by JMX clients such as jConsole, or other JMX clients that use the Attach API.

feature.name: logstashCollector-1.0
feature.description: Logstash collector gathers data from various sources and forwards the data to a Logstash server using Lumberjack protocol.

feature.name: managedBeans-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for the Managed Beans 1.0 specification. Managed Beans provide a common foundation for different Java EE components types that are managed by a container. Common services provided to Managed Beans include resource injection, lifecycle management and the use of interceptors.

feature.name: mdb-3.2
feature.description: This feature enables the use of Message-Driven Enterprise JavaBeans written to the EJB 3.2 specification. MDBs allow asynchronous processing of messages within a Java EE component.

feature.name: microProfile-1.0
feature.description: This feature combines the Liberty features that support Eclipse MicroProfile 1.0 for Cloud Native Java.

feature.name: microProfile-1.2
feature.description: This feature combines the Liberty features that support Eclipse MicroProfile 1.2 for Cloud Native Java.

feature.name: microProfile-1.3
feature.description: This feature combines the Liberty features that support Eclipse MicroProfile 1.3 for Cloud Native Java.

feature.name: microProfile-1.4
feature.description: This feature combines the Liberty features that support Eclipse MicroProfile 1.4 for Cloud Native Java.

feature.name: microProfile-2.0
feature.description: This feature combines the Liberty features that support Eclipse MicroProfile 2.0 for Cloud Native Java.

feature.name: microProfile-2.1
feature.description: This feature combines the Liberty features that support Eclipse MicroProfile 2.1 for Cloud Native Java.

feature.name: microProfile-2.2
feature.description: This feature combines the Liberty features that support Eclipse MicroProfile 2.2 for Cloud Native Java.

feature.name: microProfile-3.0
feature.description: This feature combines the Liberty features that support Eclipse MicroProfile 3.0 for Cloud Native Java.

feature.name: microProfile-3.2
feature.description: This feature combines the Liberty features that support Eclipse MicroProfile 3.2 for Cloud Native Java.

feature.name: mongodb-2.0
feature.description: This feature has been stabilized. The strategic alternative to this feature is described at https://openliberty.io/blog/2019/02/19/mongodb-with-open-liberty.html. This feature enables the usage of the MongoDB Java Driver and allows DB instances to be configured in the server configuration, injected into managed components such as EJBs, and accessed through JNDI. Applications interact with these DB instances via the MongoDB APIs

feature.name: monitor-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables the Performance Monitoring Infrastructure (PMI) for other features the server is running. Monitoring data is accessible through standard MXBeans; access through the traditional WebSphere Perf MBean can be enabled.

feature.name: mpConfig-1.1
feature.description: The Eclipse MicroProfile Config specification provides a unified mechanism to access configuration, providing a single view of multiple sources.

feature.name: mpConfig-1.2
feature.description: The Eclipse MicroProfile Config specification provides a unified mechanism to access configuration, providing a single view of multiple sources.

feature.name: mpConfig-1.3
feature.description: The Eclipse MicroProfile Config specification provides a unified mechanism to access configuration, providing a single view of multiple sources.

feature.name: mpContextPropagation-1.0
feature.description: This feature implements the MicroProfile Context Propagation 1.0 specification, which allows you to obtain class instances of CompletableFuture that are backed by an instance of ManagedExecutor and provides the ability to contextualize CompletableFuture actions.

feature.name: mpFaultTolerance-1.0
feature.description: This feature provides support for the Eclipse MicroProfile Fault Tolerance specification.

feature.name: mpFaultTolerance-1.1
feature.description: This feature provides support for the Eclipse MicroProfile Fault Tolerance 1.1 specification.

feature.name: mpFaultTolerance-2.0
feature.description: This feature provides support for the MicroProfile Fault Tolerance 2.0 API.

feature.name: mpHealth-1.0
feature.description: This feature provides support for the Eclipse MicroProfile Health specification.

feature.name: mpHealth-2.0
feature.description: This feature provides support for the Eclipse MicroProfile Health specification.

feature.name: mpHealth-2.1
feature.description: This feature provides support for the Eclipse MicroProfile Health specification.

feature.name: mpJwt-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables web applications or microservices to use the Eclipse JSON Web Token 1.0 specification to authenticate users instead of, or in addition to, the configured user registry.

feature.name: mpJwt-1.1
feature.description: This feature enables web applications or microservices to use the Eclipse JSON Web Token 1.1 specification to authenticate users instead of, or in addition to, the configured user registry.

feature.name: mpMetrics-1.0
feature.description: This feature provides support for the Eclipse MicroProfile Metrics specification for enterprise Java.

feature.name: mpMetrics-1.1
feature.description: This feature provides support for the Eclipse MicroProfile Metrics specification for enterprise Java.

feature.name: mpMetrics-2.0
feature.description: This feature provides support for the Eclipse MicroProfile Metrics 2.0 specification for enterprise Java.

feature.name: mpMetrics-2.2
feature.description: This feature provides support for the Eclipse MicroProfile Metrics 2.2 specification for enterprise Java.

feature.name: mpOpenAPI-1.0
feature.description: This feature provides support for the Eclipse MicroProfile OpenAPI specification for enterprise Java.

feature.name: mpOpenAPI-1.1
feature.description: This feature provides support for the Eclipse MicroProfile OpenAPI specification for enterprise Java.

feature.name: mpOpenTracing-1.0
feature.description: The Eclipse MicroProfile OpenTracing specification provides a mechanism to access an opentracing.io Tracer.

feature.name: mpOpenTracing-1.1
feature.description: The MicroProfile OpenTracing specification provides a mechanism to access an opentracing.io Tracer.

feature.name: mpOpenTracing-1.2
feature.description: The MicroProfile OpenTracing specification provides a mechanism to access an opentracing.io Tracer.

feature.name: mpOpenTracing-1.3
feature.description: The MicroProfile OpenTracing specification provides a mechanism to access an opentracing.io Tracer.

feature.name: mpReactiveMessaging-1.0
feature.description: The Eclipse MicroProfile Reactive Messaging specification provides asynchronous messaging support based on Reactive Streams for MicroProfile.

feature.name: mpReactiveStreams-1.0
feature.description: This feature provides support for the MicroProfile Reactive Streams 1.0 API

feature.name: mpRestClient-1.0
feature.description: The Eclipse MicroProfile Rest Client specification provides a type-safe mechanism for invoking RESTful services.

feature.name: mpRestClient-1.1
feature.description: The MicroProfile Rest Client specification provides a type-safe mechanism for invoking RESTful services.

feature.name: mpRestClient-1.2
feature.description: The MicroProfile Rest Client specification provides a type-safe mechanism for invoking RESTful services.

feature.name: mpRestClient-1.3
feature.description: The MicroProfile Rest Client specification provides a type-safe mechanism for invoking RESTful services.

feature.name: oauth-2.0
feature.description: This feature enables web applications to integrate OAuth 2.0 for authenticating and authorizing users.

feature.name: openapi-3.1
feature.description: This feature enables users to discover and understand REST APIs exposed by web applications and Liberty components that use the OpenAPI 3.0 specification.

feature.name: openid-2.0
feature.description: This feature enables web applications to integrate OpenID 2.0 for authenticating users instead of, or in addition to, the configured user registry.

feature.name: openidConnectClient-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables web applications to integrate OpenID Connect Client 1.0 for authenticating users instead of, or in addition to, the configured user registry.

feature.name: openidConnectServer-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables web applications to integrate OpenID Connect Server 1.0 for authenticating users instead of, or in addition to, the configured user registry.

feature.name: opentracing-1.0
feature.description: This feature provides support for Opentracing function for enterprise Java.

feature.name: opentracing-1.1
feature.description: This feature provides support for Opentracing function for enterprise Java.

feature.name: opentracing-1.2
feature.description: This feature provides support for Opentracing function for enterprise Java.

feature.name: opentracing-1.3
feature.description: This feature provides support for Opentracing function for enterprise Java.

feature.name: osgiConsole-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables an OSGi console to aid debug of the runtime. It can be used to display information about bundles, packages and services which may be useful when developing your own features for product extensions.

feature.name: passwordUtilities-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for obtaining the values of the user and password attributes of authData elements from an application, and also allows the use of the com.ibm.websphere.crypto.PasswordUtil class as an API.

feature.name: requestTiming-1.0
feature.description: Provides warnings and diagnostic info for slow or hung requests.

feature.name: restConnector-2.0
feature.description: A secure, REST administrative connector that can be used locally or remotely using any Java developer kit. This connector enables remote access from a Java client or directly through an HTTPS call. The administrator and reader roles protect the connector. The connector requires TLS to keep the communication confidential. The HTTPS port used by the connector is defined through the default HTTP endpoint. This feature supersedes the restConnector-1.0 feature. It enables the REST handler configuration APIs. When this feature is combined with features supporting configuration validation, the corresponding REST handler validation APIs are enabled.

feature.name: samlWeb-2.0
feature.description: This feature enables web applications to use SAML web single sign-on version 2.0 function.

feature.name: servlet-3.1
feature.description: This feature enables support for HTTP Servlets written to the Java Servlet 3.1 specification. You can package servlets in Java EE specified WAR or EAR files. If servlet security is required, you should also configure an appSecurity feature. Without a security feature, any security constraints for the application are ignored.

feature.name: servlet-4.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for HTTP Servlets written to the Java Servlet 4.0 specification. You can package servlets in Java EE specified WAR or EAR files. If servlet security is required, you should also configure an appSecurity feature. Without a security feature, any security constraints for the application are ignored.

feature.name: sessionCache-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables persistence of HTTP sessions using JCache. Persisting HTTP session data using JCache allows for high performance HTTP session persistence without the use of a relational database. Failover of HTTP sessions can be achieved by configuring multiple servers to persist data to the same location.

feature.name: sessionDatabase-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables persistence of HTTP sessions to a datasource using JDBC. Persisting HTTP session data to a database allows recovery of the data after a server restart or unexpected server failure. Failover of HTTP sessions can be achieved by configuring multiple servers to persist data to the same location

feature.name: sipServlet-1.1
feature.description: This feature enables support for SIP Servlets written to the Java SipServlet 1.1 specification. The servlets can be packaged in Java EE specified WAR, SAR or EAR files. If servlet security is required, an appSecurity feature should also be configured; in the absence of a security feature any security constraints for the application will be ignored.

feature.name: socialLogin-1.0
feature.description: Social Media Login feature provides a form of single sign-on (SSO) that enables users to sign in to a secured website by using their existing social media account.

feature.name: spnego-1.0
feature.displayName: Simple and Protected GSSAPI Negotiation Mechanism 1.0
feature.description: This feature enables web applications to integrate SPNEGO 1.0 for authenticating users instead of, or in addition to, the configured user registry.

feature.name: springBoot-1.5
feature.description: This feature enables support for Spring Boot applications using Spring Boot version 1.5.x.

feature.name: springBoot-2.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for Spring Boot applications using Spring Boot version 2.0.x.

feature.name: ssl-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) connections. The secure HTTPS listener is not started unless the ssl-1.0 feature is enabled and a keystore is configured.

feature.name: transportSecurity-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) connections. The secure HTTPS listener is not started unless the transportSecurity-1.0 feature is enabled and a keystore is configured.

feature.name: wasJmsClient-2.0
feature.description: The wasJmsClient-2.0 feature provides applications with access to the message queues that are hosted on WebSphere Application Server through the JMS 2.0 API. This feature supersedes wasJmsClient-1.1. The wasJmsClient-2.0 feature is compliant with JMS 2.0 specifications and is supported only on JDK 7 or later. It enables access to the messaging engine that is enabled through the wasJmsServer feature, and also to the service integration bus that is hosted on a full profile server.

feature.name: wasJmsSecurity-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables the WebSphere Embedded Messaging Server to authenticate and authorize access from JMS clients.

feature.name: wasJmsServer-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables an embedded messaging server that is JMS compliant. Applications can send and receive messages using the wasJmsClient feature.

feature.name: webCache-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables local caching for web responses. It includes the distributedMap feature and performs automatic caching of web application responses to improve response times and throughput. Applications can include a cache-spec.xml file to customize the response caching. The cache may be distributed through addition of a network cache provider such as WebSphere eXtreme Scale.

feature.name: webProfile-7.0
feature.description: This feature combines the Liberty features that support the Java EE 7.0 Web Profile.

feature.name: webProfile-8.0
feature.description: This feature combines the Liberty features that support the Java EE 8.0 Web Profile.

feature.name: websocket-1.0
feature.description: This feature enables support for WebSocket applications written to the Java API for WebSocket 1.0 specification.

feature.name: websocket-1.1
feature.description: This feature enables support for WebSocket applications written to the Java API for WebSocket 1.1 specification.

feature.name: wsAtomicTransaction-1.2
feature.description: This feature enables support for Atomic Transaction for XML-Based Web Services 2.2.

feature.name: wsSecurity-1.1
feature.description: This feature provides support for securing JAX-WS web services using a WS-Security policy.

feature.name: wsSecuritySaml-1.1
feature.description: This feature enables the SAML Assertion in the Web Service Security version 1.1 function.
